derivation.yuyuan_name: mid 17th cent.: from obsolete Dutch klinckaerd (earlier form of klinker), from klinken 'to clink'
late 17th cent. (denoting a person or thing that clinks): from clink + -er. Sense 2 dates from the mid 19th cent., sense 1 (with depreciatory reference) from the 1930s

means.word_mean: 1. a fragment of incombustible matter left after a wood or coal or charcoal fire
2. a hard brick used as a paving stone

2. turn to clinker or form clinker under excessive heat in burning
